entry.title: WebRTC HW encoders: Do SW fallback if resolution is less than 360p.
entry.content:
Manual HW vs SW quality testing has revealed that, to little surprise,

the lowest resolutions provide inferior quality, especially if bitrate

constrained. The HW encoders also don't like some resolutions due to

divisibility, but today we already avoid e.g. 270p due to not being

divisible by 4 so this already triggers SW for some HW encoders like

MediaFoundationVideoEncodeAccelerator. But 180p and other resolutions

suffer from bad quality. The breakeven point appears to be around 360p.



This CL puts the "avoid < 360p HW" check in RTCVideoEncoder rather than

on individual encoder implementations for two reasons:

1. This limits the logic to WebRTC meaning we don't break WebCodecs.

2. The quality issue appears to be similar on all implementations tested

so far, power efficiency is less of a problem for lower resolutions

anyway, and we don't have to duplicate this logic in multiple places.



TESTED=See repro steps in https://crbug.com/1448816 as well as quality

screenshots of before and after the fix: https://crbug.com/1448816#c3

Not every unit test suite currently creates a HostResolverManager using the UrlRequestContextBuilder, so this change does keep usage of DefaultClientSocketFactory if a RequestImpl's ResolveContext is null.

entry.title: iwa: Extract Update Manifest parsing logic from policy handling
entry.content:
This CL extracts the update manifest downloading and parsing logic into

a standalone class, `IsolatedWebAppUpdateManifestFetcher`. This is in

preparation for re-using the update manifest processing for implementing

updating of IWAs.



This CL also introduces a new `UpdateManifest` class, which acts as a

thin wrapper around the data contained in an update manifest.



The parsing logic is now also aligned more closely to the explainer:

- Additional fields are ignored.

- Invalid URLs or versions are ignored, instead of failing parsing.

entry.title: Add open64 for Large File System support to gzlib.
entry.content:
The convention of large file support is passing 3 build flags -D_LARGEFILE_SOURCE -D_FILE_OFFSET_BITS=64 -D_LARGEFILE64_SOURCE. Then we can expect open(), lseek(), fopen(), etc. calls to be defined as the LFS-enabled counterparts like open64(), fopen64().



zlib doesn't follow the convention of large file support on Linux and undefines the build flag -D_FILE_OFFSET_BITS=64 in gzguts.h included by gzlib.c. We decide to have a local fix in gzlib.c without an intrusive fix to gzguts.h. This looks to be fine because lseek64 is handled similarly.

entry.title: [scroll-animations] Avoid scroll/view-timeline-attachment in WPTs
entry.content:
These properties will be removed from the spec [1]. The new property

timeline-scope offers similar functionality.



This CL is mostly a self-explanatory migration from

*-timeline-attachment to timeline-scope, with a few exceptions:



- The test id=timeline_ancestor_scroll_timeline_wins_on_same_element

needed more severe adjustment, because deferred timelines are

no longer typed (that is, a deferred timeline is not a

scroll timeline nor a view timeline), so that test had

to be refactored to avoid using deferred timelines.

- A few tests in view-timeline-dynamic.html were refactored to avoid

timeline-scope, as timeline-scope was not essential for those tests.



[1] https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/7759

entry.title: [DNR] Ensure iframes are uncollapsed after being readded to DOM
entry.content:
The declarativeNetRequest API takes care to "collapse" (hide) iframes

that it blocks. Should such an iframe be unblocked and reloaded, the

element is uncollapsed again. Unfortunately however, that didn't work

if the iframe was removed from the DOM and readded before it was

unblocked. When the iframe was added back to the DOM, the

FrameTreeNode was recreated and its collapsed state lost.



To fix that, let's have HTMLFrameOwnerElement::DisconnectContent()

clear the HTMLIFrameElement's collapsed state too. That way, the

collapsed state for the HTMLIFrameElement and FrameTreeNode are kept

in sync, and the iframe can be collapsed again as necessary.

entry.title: CCNS BFCache: evict CCNS BFCache when HTTP auth is required
entry.content:
If `StoragePartitionImpl::OnAuthRequired()` is called, it means the

URLLoader receives 401/407 for some page even after attempting to

authenticate with auth cache. If there is any BFCache entries with

CCNS header from the same origin, we should evict them since they may

contain some sensitive information from the previous authenticated

entry.title: Use no PrefService for GetUserAgentMetadata in WebView
entry.content:
WebView previously used a profile specific PrefService for user agent

metadata computation. This changes the computation to use no PrefService

at all. This reflects the behavior in most other embedders (but not

Chrome, where a browser-wide, profile inspecific local_state PrefService

is used).



Note that WebView did not previously set any of the key-values used by

the underlying embedder_support::GetUserAgentMetadata function, so this

should not change behavior.



This CL also clarifies the use of a PrefService in

AwClientHintsControllerDeligate, due to potential confusion when

comparing it to the one in client_hints::ClientHints.



Bug: 1446913

entry.title: [PA] Deflake PartitionAllocThreadCacheTest on iOS and Mac bots.
entry.content:
PartitionAllocThreadCacheTest.MultipleThreadCachesAccounting and

ThreadCacheRegistry depend on that there are no thread caches except

main thread's. However iOS and Mac create worker threads internally via

start_wqthread (this seemd not to be controlled by user code).

So If PartitionAlloc as Malloc is enabled, thread caches are created

for the worker threads. This causes the tests failure.



So remove the assumption from the tests when running tests on iOS and

Mac with PartitionAlloc as Malloc enabled.

entry.title: COOP: restrict-properties 6.5/*: BCG information for remote RVHs.
entry.content:
Precedent patch introduced an incorrect behavior:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4498711/comment/fef0fea1_3b86445a/



The browsing context group that is sent at creation time in

RenderViewHosts should be the browsing context group of the current

documents on the page. RVH's site_instance_group() is the browsing

context group that holds the representation in the case of RVHs to

page in another browsing context group. This causes incorrect

information to be sent during cross browsing context group navigations.



Went back to the previous variation and added a comment describing the

reasoning. Tests covering this case are added as part of the 8th patch:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4546181. See

CoopRestrictPropertiesBrowserTest.SimpleRemotePopup for an example.

entry.title: Introduce kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp feature
entry.content:
This CL introduces kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp

feature. kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp keeps track of anchor tag, and

warms up the relevant service workers in the following timings.



- If sw_warm_up_on_visible is true, and when the anchor becomes visible.

- if sw_warm_up_on_pointerover is true, and when the mouse hovers on the anchor.

- if sw_warm_up_on_pointerdown is true, and when the mouse button is pressed on the anchor.



sw_warm_up_max_count feature param controls the maximum number of

service workers that is warmed-up.



Not to prevent navigation and loading, kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp

waits for onload. After onload, the accumulated URLs are sent to the

browser process, and will be processed to warm up service workers. After

onload, If any events that can warm up service workers happen, these URL

candidates will be sent to the browser process immediately.







This CL adds AnchorElementObserverForServiceWorker class. This class

observes the following events.



- anchor becomes visible

- pointer over

- pointer down

- onload



AnchorElementObserverForServiceWorker gathers URLs, and send them to the

browser process by using

MaybeStartOutermostMainFrameNavigation().



In the browser side,

RenderFrameHostImpl::MaybeStartOutermostMainFrameNavigation

receives URL candidates, and passes it to WarmUpServiceWorker()

function. WarmUpServiceWorker() function stores the request into

ServiceWorkerContextCore.



ServiceWorkerContextWrapper warms up a service worker if there is a

remaining warm-up request. This process is done one-by-one in

serial. MaybeProcessPendingWarmUpRequest() function does this serial

warm-up operation recursively.
